4. 4. aliquid: this is the manuscript reading, changed by most editors to aliud. There are two objections to it: from its connection we should expect quidquam, and it is also somewhat irregular (but quite in the style of Tacitus) to have it followed by quam (some such word as potius being understood). But the distinction between aliquis and quisquam was some· what obscured in the later writers, just as the corresponding words some and any are constantly confused by foreigners. 8. 3. urbanis quingenos: supplied from Suet. Oct. 101 and Dio, LVI. 32. It is more probable that the omission was due to a scribe's oversight than that Tacitus was ignorant of the fact or, knowing it, failed to state it.

4. insignes: in the manuscript this word is followed by visi [sc. sunt]‚ and some editors insert qui as its subject, before insignes. The reading here given is supported by 77. 5, multa decernuntur, ex quis maxime in· signia ne, etc.
